From the set 🎬

This is not your typical tripod head.

Geared heads allow filmmakers to control framing with extreme precision using gear-driven wheels.

Long before modern fluid heads became standard, geared heads were already used in classic cinema to achieve smooth, accurate and repeatable movements.

Today, they remain essential whenever a shot demands absolute control.

Some of the most well-known models in the industry include:
Mitchell, Moy, Worrall and the classic Arrihead.

They are used on tripods as well as in more complex setups like cranes or remote heads, where every micro adjustment matters.

But there’s something you don’t see at first glance:
this is not something anyone can just pick up.

Operating a geared head requires coordination, sensitivity and hours of practice. 
In many rental houses, operators train using lasers and guides to master the movement.

Because this is not improvised — it’s trained.

